            <p:rationale>Information, applications, application components, etc. - all these must have a common definition across the enterprise to enable a mutual understanding between involved parties. A common vocabulary can facilitate communication and prevent misunderstandings, misinterpretations and thus avoid unwanted results.
Moreover, the common vocabulary makes a vital basis for effective and efficient data exchange and data sharing within the information system.</p:rationale>
            <p:implications>A unified terminology and common understanding are keys to success in the information environment.
The enterprise must initially establish a common vocabulary that will be used uniformly across the enterprise.
There must be the role of a data administrator (or a vocabulary administrator) that will be responsible for accuracy and currency of this vocabulary. Whenever a new data definition is required, the administrator should reconcile the terminology and update the vocabulary, if necessary.
Ambiguities and conflicts resulting from multiple definitions used by individual departments in the enterprise must give way to accepted enterprise-wide definitions and understanding.
As the enterprises become more and more dependent on information and technologies processing the data, a mutual understanding - driven by the common vocabulary - is vital for an effective usage of information and evolution of the information environment.</p:implications>
